{
  "type": "ux",
  "title": "Progressive TTS: speak streamed AI reply sentence-by-sentence (perceived speed)",
  "description": "Currently in Conversation.tsx, TTS only fires after the streaming SSE reply finishes (`tts.speak(streamedText)` inside the `else` branch around line 864 after `await api.streamMessage(...)` resolves). With ~15s end-to-end latency the user hears nothing for many seconds even though tokens are arriving. This proposal addresses the PERF-HIGH backlog item (faster perceived response) as a UX feature: start speaking each completed sentence as soon as it streams in, so the AI's voice begins within ~1-2s of the first token.\n\nChanges:\n\n1. `frontend/src/hooks/useSpeechSynthesis.ts`\n   - Add a new method `enqueue(text: string, lang?: string, rateOverride?: number)` that appends sentences to an internal FIFO queue (`pendingRef = useRef<SpeechSynthesisUtterance[]>([])`) and drains them sequentially via `utterance.onend` chaining without calling `speechSynthesis.cancel()` first.\n   - Add `flush()` to mark end-of-stream so the hook knows no more chunks are coming (used to keep `isSpeaking` true between utterances).\n   - `stop()` must clear the queue AND call `cancel()`.\n   - Each enqueued utterance still runs through `sanitizeForSpeech()` and uses the same voice/volume/rate logic as `speak()`.\n   - `speak()` keeps existing behavior (cancels then speaks) for backwards compatibility (used by /start opening, vocab pronunciation, replays).\n\n2. `frontend/src/pages/Conversation.tsx`\n   - In `sendMessage`, maintain a local `let spokenUpTo = 0;` cursor and a `let speakBuffer = '';` accumulator.\n   - Inside `onChunk`, after updating `streamedText`, scan `streamedText.slice(spokenUpTo)` for sentence terminators using regex `/[^.!?\\n]*[.!?\\n]+\\s*/g`. For each complete match, call `tts.enqueue(match)` and advance `spokenUpTo`.\n   - In the streaming-success branch (around line 864), replace `tts.speak(streamedText)` with: enqueue any tail `streamedText.slice(spokenUpTo)` if non-empty, then `tts.flush()`. Do NOT call the old `speak(streamedText)` (would re-speak everything).\n   - Fallback path (non-streaming `else if (streamFailed)`) continues to use `tts.speak(res.message)` unchanged.\n   - Guard with a feature flag-like check: only enqueue progressively when `tts.isSupported`. Existing TTS volume slider / mute behavior must keep working (queue respects current `volumeRef`).\n\n3. `frontend/src/utils/sanitizeForSpeech.ts` ‚Äî no change required (already used by hook).\n\n4. Add a small unit test `frontend/src/hooks/useSpeechSynthesis.test.ts` (new file) using vitest + jsdom mocking `window.speechSynthesis`: verify (a) `enqueue` called twice results in two utterances spoken in order (simulate `onend`), (b) `stop()` clears pending utterances, (c) `enqueue` after `stop()` works again.\n\nNo backend changes, no schema changes, no migrations. Existing streaming endpoint already emits chunk events suitable for sentence detection. The change is small/focused and directly improves perceived responsiveness of every conversation turn ‚Äî the user hears the assistant speaking within ~1-2s of streaming start instead of after the full ~15s response completes.",
  "files_to_modify": [
    "frontend/src/hooks/useSpeechSynthesis.ts",
    "frontend/src/pages/Conversation.tsx",
    "frontend/src/hooks/useSpeechSynthesis.test.ts"
  ],
  "priority": "high",
  "estimated_complexity": "medium"
}
